+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DhANWg13xzToj77VpGM5xi","type":"tool_result","content":" RUN  v2.1.9 /workspace\n\n ✓ tests/plugins/asset-pipeline.test.ts > asset-pipeline plugin > rewrites relative image URLs to /assets/ path\n ✓ tests/plugins/asset-pipeline.test.ts > asset-pipeline plugin > rewrites relative link URLs to /assets/ path\n ✓ tests/plugins/asset-pipeline.test.ts > asset-pipeline plugin > leaves absolute URLs unchanged\n ✓ tests/plugins/asset-pipeline.test.ts > asset-pipeline plugin > generates asset manifest in ctx.data\n ✓ tests/plugins/asset-pipeline.test.ts > asset-pipeline plugin > handles files with no asset references\n ✓ tests/plugins/asset-pipeline.test.ts > asset-pipeline plugin > handles multiple assets in one file\n ✓ tests/plugins/asset-pipeline.test.ts > asset-pipeline plugin > asset manifest includes all discovered assets\n ✓ tests/plugins/asset-pipeline.test.ts > asset-pipeline plugin > does not double-process already-rewritten URLs\n\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  8 passed (8)\n   Start at  01:12:59\n   Duration  1.29s (transform 46ms, setup 0ms, collect 43ms, tests 7ms, environment 0ms, prepare 57ms)","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JM5Bxd8gXPXdwRFsHS67JM","session_id":"be6ab0bb-ca1c-43bc-a268-31f580a00a9d","uuid":"65caf0dc-8adf-4a57-99aa-96c95b7eae88"}
+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JM5Bxd8gXPXdwRFsHS67JM","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 75 tests pass. Now I have completed reading all source files, test files, and core infrastructure. Here is my comprehensive review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review Report: Plugin Implementations\n\n**Scope**: 8 plugins in `/workspace/src/plugins/`, tested by 8 test suites in `/workspace/tests/plugins/`\n**Current Test Status**: All 75 tests pass (9 test files, 75 total tests)\n\n---\n\n### HIGH Priority Findings\n\n#### HIGH-1: `rss-feed.ts` -- Incorrect dependency declaration\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, line 7\n\n```typescript\ndependencies: ['markdown-ext', 'taxonomy'],\n```\n\nThe rss-feed plugin declares a dependency on `markdown-ext`, but it does not consume any data produced by `markdown-ext`. It reads `ctx.files` (which would already be transformed by the time `afterBuild` runs, regardless of dependency order since `transformContent` runs in a separate phase) and `file.tags` (a native property of `ContentFile`). It does not read `ctx.data` keys set by `markdown-ext` (there are none -- `markdown-ext` sets no data keys).\n\nThe dependency on `taxonomy` is similarly questionable. The plugin reads `file.tags` directly from the `ContentFile` interface, not from the `taxonomy-tags` data key. The test on line 67-75 of `/workspace/tests/plugins/rss-feed.test.ts` sets up taxonomy data in `ctx.data`, but the plugin implementation never reads it -- it uses `file.tags` directly.\n\n**Impact**: The dependency graph is misleading. If `markdown-ext` or `taxonomy` were removed from the system, the rss-feed plugin would still work identically. More critically, if plugin resolution fails because `markdown-ext` or `taxonomy` is not registered, it would unnecessarily prevent `rss-feed` from functioning. This is a correctness issue in the declared contract.\n\n**Recommendation**: Either remove the unnecessary dependencies, or if the intent is that `rss-feed` should always run after `markdown-ext` (to get HTML-transformed content) and `taxonomy` (to get tags populated), document this clearly. Note that the engine architecture already guarantees `transformContent` runs for all plugins before any `afterBuild` hooks, so the `markdown-ext` dependency is not needed for content transformation ordering.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-2: `search-index.ts` -- Incorrect dependency declaration\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/search-index.ts`, line 7\n\n```typescript\ndependencies: ['markdown-ext', 'syntax-highlight'],\n```\n\nSame issue as HIGH-1. The `search-index` plugin only uses `ctx.files` in its `afterBuild` hook. It does not read any data from `ctx.data` keys set by `markdown-ext` or `syntax-highlight`. The engine guarantees that all `transformContent` hooks run before any `afterBuild` hooks (see `/workspace/src/core/engine.ts`, lines 62-77 vs lines 99-104), so even the implicit \"I need transformed content\" argument does not justify these as dependencies.\n\nThese dependencies create unnecessary coupling. If `syntax-highlight` or `markdown-ext` were not registered, the engine would throw `Missing dependency: search-index requires markdown-ext` even though the plugin would work fine without them.\n\n**Recommendation**: Same as HIGH-1.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-3: `sitemap.ts` -- Non-deterministic URL ordering may cause fragile tests\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/sitemap.ts`, lines 13-15\n\n```typescript\nfor (const key of output.keys()) {\n  if (key === 'sitemap.xml') continue;\n  urls.push(`${config.baseUrl}/${key}`);\n}\n```\n\nThe sitemap iterates `ctx.output.keys()`, which for a JavaScript `Map` yields keys in insertion order. This means the sitemap URL ordering depends entirely on the order that other plugins insert entries into `ctx.output`. In an integrated build with multiple plugins (taxonomy, rss-feed, content pages), the order will depend on plugin execution order, which is determined by dependency resolution.\n\nThe current tests pass because each test sets up a fresh `Map` with controlled insertion order. However, in a real integrated scenario, if plugin execution order changes (e.g., dependency graph is modified), the sitemap output would change silently. This is not a test-failure bug today, but an architectural fragility.\n\n**Impact**: The sitemap output is not sorted, making it non-deterministic relative to plugin registration order changes. This could cause diff-based deployment pipelines to detect false changes.\n\n**Recommendation**: Sort the URLs alphabetically before generating the XML:\n\n```typescript\nurls.sort();\n```\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-4: `asset-pipeline.ts` -- Regex does not handle single-quoted attributes or unquoted attributes\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts`, lines 14-29\n\n```typescript\ncontent = content.replace(\n  /src=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g,\n  ...\n);\ncontent = content.replace(\n  /href=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g,\n  ...\n);\n```\n\nThese regexes only match double-quoted attribute values (`src=\"./file\"`). They will not match:\n- Single-quoted: `src='./image.png'`\n- Paths with subdirectories will be rewritten flatly: `src=\"./images/photo.png\"` becomes `src=\"/assets/images/photo.png\"` (which may or may not be intended)\n\nThe current tests only test double-quoted attributes, so all tests pass. But this is a gap in real-world HTML handling.\n\n**Impact**: Medium-to-high in production; the tests mask this because they only exercise double-quoted forms. If upstream markdown processors or user content use single quotes, assets will not be rewritten.\n\n**Recommendation**: Either expand the regex to handle both quote types, or document the limitation explicitly.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM Priority Findings\n\n#### MEDIUM-1: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Footnote reference replacement is too greedy (removes definition markers too)\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 20-23\n\n```typescript\n// Remove footnote definitions from content\ncontent = content.replace(/^\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]:\\s*(.+)$/gm, '');\n\n// Replace footnote references [^1] with sup links\ncontent = content.replace(/\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]/g, '<sup><a href=\"#fn-$1\">$1</a></sup>');\n```\n\nThe order here is correct: definitions are removed first, then references are replaced. However, the definition removal regex leaves behind empty lines. These empty lines are then processed through the paragraph-wrapping logic. While the final `content.replace(/\\n{3,}/g, '\\n\\n')` cleans up triple-or-more newlines, double blank lines from removed footnote definitions can still leave artifacts.\n\nThe tests pass because the test expectations are loose enough (e.g., `toContain` checks), but the actual output may contain unexpected extra whitespace or empty `<p></p>` tags depending on the input structure.\n\n**Impact**: In edge cases with footnote definitions surrounded by blank lines, the output could contain empty paragraph tags. Current tests do not exercise this.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-2: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Admonition regex requires `\\n` after `:::type` but content may use `\\r\\n`\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, line 26\n\n```typescript\ncontent = content.replace(/^:::(\\w+)\\n([\\s\\S]*?)^:::/gm, (_match, type: string, body: string) => {\n```\n\nThis regex uses a literal `\\n` between the admonition type and body. If content uses Windows-style line endings (`\\r\\n`), the regex will not match. The `[\\s\\S]*?` in the body would handle mixed line endings, but the explicit `\\n` after `:::(\\w+)` will not match `\\r\\n`.\n\n**Impact**: The plugin would silently fail to convert admonitions in content with Windows line endings. Tests pass because test strings use Unix line endings.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-3: `markdown-ext.ts` -- `applyInline` bold/italic regex has ordering conflict\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 103-106\n\n```typescript\nfunction applyInline(text: string): string {\n  // Bold **text**\n  text = text.replace(/\\*\\*(.+?)\\*\\*/g, '<strong>$1</strong>');\n  // Italic *text*\n  text = text.replace(/\\*(.+?)\\*/g, '<em>$1</em>');\n```\n\nThe bold regex runs first, which is correct for preventing `***text***` from being partially consumed. However, consider the input `*italic* and **bold**`. After bold replacement: `*italic* and <strong>bold</strong>`. After italic replacement: `<em>italic</em> and <strong>bold</strong>`. This works correctly.\n\nBut consider `***bold italic***`. After bold: `*<strong>bold italic</strong>*` (the `(.+?)` is non-greedy and matches inside the triple stars). Wait -- actually the regex `\\*\\*(.+?)\\*\\*` on `***bold italic***` would match `**` at position 0, then `.+?` captures `*bold italic`, then `**` matches the last two stars, producing `<strong>*bold italic</strong>*`. The trailing `*` would then not match the italic regex because there is no paired `*`. The output would be `<strong>*bold italic</strong>*` -- a malformed result with a literal asterisk.\n\n**Impact**: The `***bold italic***` edge case (which represents bold+italic in standard Markdown) produces malformed output. Current tests do not exercise this case, so tests pass.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-4: `taxonomy.ts` -- Tag case normalization creates mismatch with generated page filenames vs. original tag values\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/taxonomy.ts`, line 15 and line 22\n\n```typescript\nconst normalized = tag.toLowerCase();\n// ...\nctx.data.set('taxonomy-tags', tagMap);\n```\n\nAnd in `afterBuild` (line 33):\n```typescript\nconst items = files\n  .map(f => `<li><a href=\"/${f.slug}.html\">${f.title}</a></li>`)\n  .join('\\n');\n```\n\nTags are normalized to lowercase in the map keys and in the output file paths (line 45: `ctx.output.set(\\`tags/${tag}.html\\`, html)`). This is good and consistent. However, the `rss-feed` plugin reads `file.tags` directly (not the normalized values), so the RSS feed could have tags like `['JavaScript']` while the taxonomy page is at `tags/javascript.html`. This is a cross-plugin inconsistency.\n\n**Impact**: In a full build pipeline, RSS feed categories would show original-case tags (e.g., `<category>JavaScript</category>`) while taxonomy pages use lowercase (`tags/javascript.html`). This is not a test failure but a data consistency issue across plugins.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-5: `dev-server.ts` -- searchIndexPath is empty string instead of undefined when no search index exists\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/dev-server.ts`, line 24\n\n```typescript\nlet searchIndexPath = '';\n```\n\nWhen no search index exists, `searchIndexPath` remains an empty string rather than `undefined` or `null`. This is a minor semantic issue -- consumers of `dev-server-config` would need to check `searchIndexPath === ''` rather than the more idiomatic `!searchIndexPath` or `searchIndexPath === undefined`.\n\nThe tests check for this implicitly and pass, but this is inconsistent with the `assetPaths` field which uses an empty array `[]` to represent \"none\" (a clean falsy-free approach).\n\n**Impact**: Low-medium. A downstream consumer checking `if (config.searchIndexPath)` would get the correct falsy result for an empty string, but the empty string type is semantically imprecise.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-6: `rss-feed.ts` -- XML special characters in titles are not escaped\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, line 27\n\n```typescript\nreturn `    <item>\n  <title>${file.title}</title>\n  <link>${config.baseUrl}/${file.slug}.html</link>\n```\n\nIf a file title contains XML special characters like `&`, `<`, or `>` (e.g., `\"Tom & Jerry\"` or `\"A < B\"`), the generated RSS XML would be malformed. Content is wrapped in `CDATA`, so it is safe, but the `<title>` element is not.\n\nSimilarly, `config.title` on line 39 and `config.baseUrl` on line 40 are not XML-escaped.\n\n**Impact**: The RSS feed would be invalid XML if any title contains `&`, `<`, `>`, `\"`, or `'`. Current tests use simple alphanumeric titles so this is not caught.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-7: `sitemap.ts` -- Same XML escaping issue\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/sitemap.ts`, line 20\n\n```typescript\n.map(url => `  <url>\\n    <loc>${url}</loc>\\n  </url>`)\n```\n\nURLs containing `&` (e.g., query parameters) would produce invalid XML. While sitemaps typically use clean URLs without query parameters, this is still a gap.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| ID | Severity | Plugin | Issue |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| HIGH-1 | HIGH | rss-feed | Incorrect/unnecessary dependency declarations |\n| HIGH-2 | HIGH | search-index | Incorrect/unnecessary dependency declarations |\n| HIGH-3 | HIGH | sitemap | Non-deterministic URL ordering |\n| HIGH-4 | HIGH | asset-pipeline | Regex only handles double-quoted attributes |\n| MEDIUM-1 | MEDIUM | markdown-ext | Footnote removal leaves whitespace artifacts |\n| MEDIUM-2 | MEDIUM | markdown-ext | Admonition regex fails with \\r\\n line endings |\n| MEDIUM-3 | MEDIUM | markdown-ext | Bold+italic combo `***text***` produces malformed output |\n| MEDIUM-4 | MEDIUM | taxonomy | Tag case normalization not propagated to other plugins |\n| MEDIUM-5 | MEDIUM | dev-server | Empty string vs undefined for missing searchIndexPath |\n| MEDIUM-6 | MEDIUM | rss-feed | XML special characters in titles not escaped |\n| MEDIUM-7 | MEDIUM | sitemap | XML special characters in URLs not escaped |\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- All 8 plugins correctly implement the `Plugin` interface (`name`, `version`, `dependencies`, `hooks`).\n- The `ctx.data` inter-plugin communication pattern is used correctly in `asset-pipeline` (writes `asset-manifest`), `taxonomy` (writes `taxonomy-tags`), and `dev-server` (reads both, writes `dev-server-config`).\n- The `taxonomy` plugin correctly normalizes tag case to lowercase and its tests verify this.\n- The `markdown-ext` plugin handles a complex multi-pass transformation (footnotes, admonitions, block-level markdown, inline formatting) in a reasonable order of operations.\n- The `syntax-highlight` plugin correctly uses a precise regex that avoids matching inline `<code>` (only matches `<pre><code class=\"language-...\">`) and the test suite verifies this edge case.\n- Test coverage is thorough with 75 tests across 9 files, covering happy paths, empty inputs, and several edge cases.\n- All plugins use immutable patterns (`{ ...file, content }`) rather than mutating input objects, which is a good practice for the transform pipeline."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: afd348a (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 40395\ntool_uses: 26\nduration_ms: 111649</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"be6ab0bb-ca1c-43bc-a268-31f580a00a9d","uuid":"33bdb1ca-8b14-412e-9b3a-69f1761f15e4","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the 8 plugin implementations in /workspace/src/plugins/ for correctness, edge cases, and code quality. Check them against the tests in /workspace/tests/plugins/ to ensure full correctness. Look for:\n1. Any edge cases that might fail tests\n2. Code quality issues\n3. Correctness of the plugin interface implementation (name, version, dependencies, hooks)\n4. Proper handling of ctx.data for inter-plugin communication\n\nRead all 8 plugin files and all 8 test files. Report any HIGH or MEDIUM priority findings.","agentId":"afd348a","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 75 tests pass. Now I have completed reading all source files, test files, and core infrastructure. Here is my comprehensive review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review Report: Plugin Implementations\n\n**Scope**: 8 plugins in `/workspace/src/plugins/`, tested by 8 test suites in `/workspace/tests/plugins/`\n**Current Test Status**: All 75 tests pass (9 test files, 75 total tests)\n\n---\n\n### HIGH Priority Findings\n\n#### HIGH-1: `rss-feed.ts` -- Incorrect dependency declaration\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, line 7\n\n```typescript\ndependencies: ['markdown-ext', 'taxonomy'],\n```\n\nThe rss-feed plugin declares a dependency on `markdown-ext`, but it does not consume any data produced by `markdown-ext`. It reads `ctx.files` (which would already be transformed by the time `afterBuild` runs, regardless of dependency order since `transformContent` runs in a separate phase) and `file.tags` (a native property of `ContentFile`). It does not read `ctx.data` keys set by `markdown-ext` (there are none -- `markdown-ext` sets no data keys).\n\nThe dependency on `taxonomy` is similarly questionable. The plugin reads `file.tags` directly from the `ContentFile` interface, not from the `taxonomy-tags` data key. The test on line 67-75 of `/workspace/tests/plugins/rss-feed.test.ts` sets up taxonomy data in `ctx.data`, but the plugin implementation never reads it -- it uses `file.tags` directly.\n\n**Impact**: The dependency graph is misleading. If `markdown-ext` or `taxonomy` were removed from the system, the rss-feed plugin would still work identically. More critically, if plugin resolution fails because `markdown-ext` or `taxonomy` is not registered, it would unnecessarily prevent `rss-feed` from functioning. This is a correctness issue in the declared contract.\n\n**Recommendation**: Either remove the unnecessary dependencies, or if the intent is that `rss-feed` should always run after `markdown-ext` (to get HTML-transformed content) and `taxonomy` (to get tags populated), document this clearly. Note that the engine architecture already guarantees `transformContent` runs for all plugins before any `afterBuild` hooks, so the `markdown-ext` dependency is not needed for content transformation ordering.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-2: `search-index.ts` -- Incorrect dependency declaration\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/search-index.ts`, line 7\n\n```typescript\ndependencies: ['markdown-ext', 'syntax-highlight'],\n```\n\nSame issue as HIGH-1. The `search-index` plugin only uses `ctx.files` in its `afterBuild` hook. It does not read any data from `ctx.data` keys set by `markdown-ext` or `syntax-highlight`. The engine guarantees that all `transformContent` hooks run before any `afterBuild` hooks (see `/workspace/src/core/engine.ts`, lines 62-77 vs lines 99-104), so even the implicit \"I need transformed content\" argument does not justify these as dependencies.\n\nThese dependencies create unnecessary coupling. If `syntax-highlight` or `markdown-ext` were not registered, the engine would throw `Missing dependency: search-index requires markdown-ext` even though the plugin would work fine without them.\n\n**Recommendation**: Same as HIGH-1.\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-3: `sitemap.ts` -- Non-deterministic URL ordering may cause fragile tests\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/sitemap.ts`, lines 13-15\n\n```typescript\nfor (const key of output.keys()) {\n  if (key === 'sitemap.xml') continue;\n  urls.push(`${config.baseUrl}/${key}`);\n}\n```\n\nThe sitemap iterates `ctx.output.keys()`, which for a JavaScript `Map` yields keys in insertion order. This means the sitemap URL ordering depends entirely on the order that other plugins insert entries into `ctx.output`. In an integrated build with multiple plugins (taxonomy, rss-feed, content pages), the order will depend on plugin execution order, which is determined by dependency resolution.\n\nThe current tests pass because each test sets up a fresh `Map` with controlled insertion order. However, in a real integrated scenario, if plugin execution order changes (e.g., dependency graph is modified), the sitemap output would change silently. This is not a test-failure bug today, but an architectural fragility.\n\n**Impact**: The sitemap output is not sorted, making it non-deterministic relative to plugin registration order changes. This could cause diff-based deployment pipelines to detect false changes.\n\n**Recommendation**: Sort the URLs alphabetically before generating the XML:\n\n```typescript\nurls.sort();\n```\n\n---\n\n#### HIGH-4: `asset-pipeline.ts` -- Regex does not handle single-quoted attributes or unquoted attributes\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts`, lines 14-29\n\n```typescript\ncontent = content.replace(\n  /src=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g,\n  ...\n);\ncontent = content.replace(\n  /href=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g,\n  ...\n);\n```\n\nThese regexes only match double-quoted attribute values (`src=\"./file\"`). They will not match:\n- Single-quoted: `src='./image.png'`\n- Paths with subdirectories will be rewritten flatly: `src=\"./images/photo.png\"` becomes `src=\"/assets/images/photo.png\"` (which may or may not be intended)\n\nThe current tests only test double-quoted attributes, so all tests pass. But this is a gap in real-world HTML handling.\n\n**Impact**: Medium-to-high in production; the tests mask this because they only exercise double-quoted forms. If upstream markdown processors or user content use single quotes, assets will not be rewritten.\n\n**Recommendation**: Either expand the regex to handle both quote types, or document the limitation explicitly.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM Priority Findings\n\n#### MEDIUM-1: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Footnote reference replacement is too greedy (removes definition markers too)\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 20-23\n\n```typescript\n// Remove footnote definitions from content\ncontent = content.replace(/^\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]:\\s*(.+)$/gm, '');\n\n// Replace footnote references [^1] with sup links\ncontent = content.replace(/\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]/g, '<sup><a href=\"#fn-$1\">$1</a></sup>');\n```\n\nThe order here is correct: definitions are removed first, then references are replaced. However, the definition removal regex leaves behind empty lines. These empty lines are then processed through the paragraph-wrapping logic. While the final `content.replace(/\\n{3,}/g, '\\n\\n')` cleans up triple-or-more newlines, double blank lines from removed footnote definitions can still leave artifacts.\n\nThe tests pass because the test expectations are loose enough (e.g., `toContain` checks), but the actual output may contain unexpected extra whitespace or empty `<p></p>` tags depending on the input structure.\n\n**Impact**: In edge cases with footnote definitions surrounded by blank lines, the output could contain empty paragraph tags. Current tests do not exercise this.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-2: `markdown-ext.ts` -- Admonition regex requires `\\n` after `:::type` but content may use `\\r\\n`\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, line 26\n\n```typescript\ncontent = content.replace(/^:::(\\w+)\\n([\\s\\S]*?)^:::/gm, (_match, type: string, body: string) => {\n```\n\nThis regex uses a literal `\\n` between the admonition type and body. If content uses Windows-style line endings (`\\r\\n`), the regex will not match. The `[\\s\\S]*?` in the body would handle mixed line endings, but the explicit `\\n` after `:::(\\w+)` will not match `\\r\\n`.\n\n**Impact**: The plugin would silently fail to convert admonitions in content with Windows line endings. Tests pass because test strings use Unix line endings.\n\n---\n\n#### MEDIUM-3: `markdown-ext.ts` -- `applyInline` bold/italic regex has ordering conflict\n\n**File**: `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 103-106\n\n```typescript\nfunction applyInline(text: string): string {\n  // Bold **text**\n  text = text.replace(/\\*\\*(.+?)\\*\\*/g, '<strong>$1</strong>');\n  // Italic *text*\n  text = text.replace(/\\*(.+?)\\*/g, '<em>$1</em>');\n```\n\nThe bold regex runs first, which is correct for preventing `***text***` from being partially consumed. However, consider the input `*italic* and **bold**`. After bold replacement: `*italic* and <strong>bold</strong>`. After italic replacement: `<em>italic</em> and <strong>bold</strong>`. This works correctly.\n\nBut consider `***bold italic***`. After bold: `*<strong>bold italic</strong>*` (the `(.+?)` is non-greedy and matches inside the triple stars). Wait -- actua